CENTANA INTRASTATE PIPELINE, LLC, an intrastate pipeline operating within the State of Texas, will engage in the transportation of natural gas on the following terms and conditions:

CENTANA INTRASTATE PIPELINE, LLC
STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS APPLICABLE TO ALL TRANSPORTATION SERVICE (INCLUDING NGPA SECTION 311 AND TEXAS INTRASTATE SERVICE)

SECTION 1 DEFINITIONS
A. The term “business day” shall mean any day during a year, except Saturday, Sunday or Transporter’s holidays.
B. The term “Btu” shall mean British Thermal Unit and, where appropriate, the plural thereof, and the term, “MMBtu”, shall mean one million (1,000,000) Btu.
C. The term “Central Receipt Point” shall mean a Receipt Point on Transporter’s system where measurement custody transfers to Transporter.
D. The term “cubic foot” shall mean the volume of gas contained in one (1) cubic foot of space at a pressure of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths (14.73) psia and a standard temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60°F) under standard gravitational force. The average atmospheric pressure shall be assumed to be 11.3 pounds per square inch absolute.
E. The term “day” shall mean a period of twenty-four (24) consecutive hours beginning and ending at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time.
F. The term “Delivery Point” shall mean a point at the outlet side of Transporter’s facilities.
G. The term “Evaluation Period” shall mean the time period between Transporter’s receipt of Shipper’s valid request for firm transportation service and Shipper’s execution of a firm transportation agreement pursuant thereto.
H. The term “FERC” shall mean the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
I. The term “firm” or on a “firm basis” means that the capacity in Transporter’s pipeline system necessary to transport quantities of gas for the account of Shipper is not now, and will not become, subject to claim by any person other than Shipper.
J. The term “fuel” means the quantity of gas for Transporter use, line loss and other unaccounted for losses on Transporter’s Pipeline System.
K. The term “gas” shall mean natural gas as produced in its natural state that meets the quality standards contained in these general terms.
L. The term “interruptible” or on an “interruptible basis” means that the transportation of gas for the account of Shipper is subject to Transporter having sufficient capacity on Transporter’s pipeline system not dedicated to firm service at the proposed time of transportation to transport such gas at the time the gas is tendered.
M. The term “Maximum Daily Quantity” or the abbreviation “MDQ”, as used herein, shall mean the maximum quantity of gas that Transporter will transport for Shipper in any one day, as provided for in the Shipper’s transportation agreement.
N. The term “Mcf” shall mean one thousand (1,000) cubic feet of gas.
O. The term “month” shall mean a period beginning on the first (1st) day of the calendar month and extending to the first (1st) day of the following calendar month.
P. The term “NGPA” shall mean the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978.
Q. The term “Receipt Point” shall mean a point at the inlet side of Transporter’s facilities.
R. The term “Shipper” shall mean any party that has executed a transportation agreement with Transporter for transportation service subject to this Statement.
S. The term “thermally equivalent” shall mean an equal amount of heating value, expressed in Btu and measured under the specifications and conditions contained hereunder.
T. The term “transportation agreement” shall mean any contract of Transporter providing transportation service to a Shipper.
U. The term “Transporter” shall mean CENTANA INTRASTATE PIPELINE, LLC.
SECTION 2 RATES FOR SECTION 311 TRANSPORTATION SERVICE
A. The maximum monthly transportation charge for transportation service pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA shall be the maximum rate approved by the FERC for transportation by Transporter under Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA as shown in Section 24. Notwithstanding the foregoing sentence, the rate to be charged for transportation may be agreed to between Transporter and Shipper, provided that such agreed-to rate may not exceed the maximum unit rate approved by the FERC for such transportation, and provided further that such agreed-to rate may not be less than any minimum rate, if any, as approved by the FERC.
B. Transporter’s maximum rate for transportation service pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA shall be determined pursuant to Section 284.123(b)(2) of FERC’s regulations. Transporter reserves the right to file for a higher maximum rate at any time and the maximum rate which Shipper agrees to pay shall be revised to equal such higher maximum.
SECTION 3 FUEL
Fuel may be paid in kind at Shipper’s Receipt Point(s) or in dollars per MMBtu, as set forth in Shipper’s transportation service agreement.
SECTION 4 OPERATING PROVISIONS
A. Transporter is an intrastate pipeline operating in the state of Texas and is a gas utility subject to jurisdiction of the RCT. Transporter performs a “merchant function” and predominantly engages in the purchase and sale of Gas on its pipeline system in the state of Texas. Transportation services are offered on an intrastate basis and interstate basis (under Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA, or “NGPA Section 311”) pursuant to the terms of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
B. Firm Transportation Service. Subject to the operating conditions contained herein, Transporter shall receive from Shipper such daily quantities of Gas as are timely nominated by Shipper and scheduled by Transporter pursuant to Section 11, up to Shipper’s MDQ as specified in the executed transportation service agreement between Transporter and Shipper, plus the required quantity of gas for fuel, as specified in the executed firm transportation service agreement, and deliver at relatively constant flow rates an amount equal to the quantity received less the applicable fuel. This transportation service agreement shall be firm and shall not be subject to curtailment or interruptions except as provided in Sections 11 and 14 of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
C. Interruptible Transportation Service. Subject to the operating conditions contained herein, Transporter shall receive from Shipper such daily quantities of Gas as are timely nominated by Shipper and scheduled by Transporter pursuant to Section 11, up to Shipper’s MDQ, if applicable, as specified in the executed transportation service agreement between Transporter and Shipper, plus the required quantity of gas for fuel, as specified in the executed transportation service agreement, and deliver at relatively constant flow rates an amount equal to the quantity received less the applicable fuel. Interruptible transportation service shall be subject to curtailment or interruption as provided in Sections 11 and 14 of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
SECTION 5 CAPACITY AVAILABLE FOR FIRM TRANSPORTATION AGREEMENTS
A. Firm capacity that is or becomes available on Transporter’s system from time to time shall be allocated on a net present value basis. To the extent that two (2) or more requests for firm service are received during the same Evaluation Period and such requests involve the same capacity, in whole or in part, then firm capacity will be allocated to that request(s) generating the highest net present value to Transporter. Net present value will be determined based on the discounted cash flow of revenues to Transporter produced, lost, or affected by the request(s) for service. In determining the highest net present value, Transporter will consider objective criteria only. Such criteria may include, without limitation, the maximum contract quantity requested, the offered rate, the date on which the requested service would commence, and such other objective criteria available based on the requests for service received by Transporter. The net present value discount factor used by Transporter will be applied consistently to all requests for capacity within an Evaluation Period.
B. In the event that Transporter receives two (2) or more requests for firm service which produce an equivalent net present value, any available capacity will be allocated between or among such requests on a pro rata basis; provided, however, if one or more party(s) is offered capacity on a pro rata basis pursuant to this Section and any party declines to contract for such capacity, such party’s request shall be deemed null and void and the available capacity will be reallocated among such remaining requests which produced the equivalent net present values.
C. To the extent Transporter has available unsubscribed firm capacity, Transporter reserves the right, but shall not be obligated, to reserve such capacity for a future expansion project provided that any such project is completed by the later of one (1) year from the date Transporter deems such capacity as being reserved or the date such reserved capacity actually becomes available for use.
SECTION 6 REQUESTS FOR TRANSPORTATION SERVICE
A. Transporter will accept as valid only those requests which are sufficiently specific with respect to the following information, all of which must be provided as set forth below:
1. Gas quantities for which transportation service is requested, stated in MMBtu per day.
2. Receipt Points: (a) Point(s) of entry into Transporter’s pipeline system. (b) Name of entity delivering gas into Transporter’s pipeline system.
3. Delivery Points: (a) Point(s) of delivery (b) Name of entities to which Transporter delivers gas on Transporter’s pipeline system.
4. Term of proposed service: (a) Date service is requested to commence. (b) Date service is requested to terminate.
5. Certification that the Shipper has a current contractual right to take possession of the gas to be delivered to Transporter for transportation and will enter into those arrangements necessary to assure all upstream and downstream transportation will be in place prior to the execution of a Transportation Agreement by Transporter.
6. The name, address, title, and telephone number of the corporate officer of Shipper who will execute the Transportation Agreement.
7. For NGPA Section 311 transportation service, a statement indicating the “on behalf of” entity(ies) that Shipper warrants meets the provisions of Section 284 of the Commission’s Regulations.
B. Unless waived by Transporter, requests for transportation service hereunder will be invalid and will not be considered if a Transportation Agreement is not entered into within forty-five (45) days of the date of receipt of the information specified in this section; provided, however, that in no event will Transporter be required to perform service hereunder prior to such time that Shipper satisfies such condition. Requests which cannot be provided due to insufficient capacity, or because of a failure to satisfy the terms of this Statement of Operating Conditions within forty-five (45) days of the date the request is made, shall not be of a continuing nature and shall be deemed a nullity for all present and future purposes.
C. Shipper may request and Transporter may agree to add or delete Receipt Points or Delivery Points on its interruptible transportation agreement. Shipper may request to add or delete Receipt Points or Delivery Points or increase or decrease its MDQ on its firm transportation agreement. Such request shall be deemed by Transporter as a new request for firm transportation service, and shall be processed by Transporter in accordance with Section 5 herein.
SECTION 7 TERM
Service will be provided for an agreed upon term; provided, however, Transporter shall have the right to terminate or suspend service immediately upon notice of such termination or suspension given to a Shipper in the event (i) Transporter, on a non-discriminatory basis, shall also concurrently terminate or suspend, as the case may be, all of its transportation services of the same type as that service which was terminated or suspended, or (ii) deliveries of gas for transportation under the Transportation Service Agreement once commenced, have ceased for any period of ninety (90) consecutive days or more and not resumed.
SECTION 8 CREDITWORTHINESS
A. Transporter shall not be required to perform or continue to perform service on behalf of any Shipper that (i) has applied for bankruptcy under any chapter of the Bankruptcy Code, (ii) has failed to make prompt and full payment to Transporter when due for transportation services rendered by Transporter, or (iii) fails to demonstrate creditworthiness as determined by Transporter on a not unduly discriminatory basis.
B. If Transporter determines that Shipper’s creditworthiness becomes unsatisfactory Transporter may require assurance of Shipper’s ability to pay or require different terms of payment. Such assurance may, at the option of Transporter, include (i) the required posting of a letter of credit in form and from a financial institution acceptable to Transporter; (ii) cash prepayments; or (iii) other delivery of other security acceptable to the Transporter. Such assurance shall be in an amount no greater than the cost of performing transportation service requested by or provided to shipper for a three (3) month period. Upon receipt of such notice, Shipper shall have two business days to provide the assurance demanded by the Transporter and the Transporter shall have the right to withhold payment, suspend deliveries from the time that the Transporter requests such assurances until such assurances are provided. In the event such assurance is not provided within two business days of receipt of notice, then a breach of the applicable transportation agreement will be deemed to have occurred and the Transporter shall be entitled to (i) terminate one or more transportation agreements with Shipper, (ii) liquidate gas balances in Transporter’s position for the purpose paying all amounts that become owing for services under any transportation agreements governed by this Statement of Conditions, and (iii) seek all other remedies available for breach of the applicable transportation agreement.
SECTION 9 NEW FACILITIES
A. Transporter shall not be required to provide any requested transportation service which would require construction or acquisition by Transporter of any new facilities or expansion of Transporter’s existing facilities. Transporter may agree to construct or acquire new facilities, or expand existing facilities, to provide service requested by any Shipper. In such event, Shipper agrees to reimburse Transporter for the total incremental cost of the new facilities or expansion of existing facilities, unless otherwise mutually agreed in writing. Transporter shall determine method of reimbursement, either lump sum or installment.
B. To the extent Transporter agrees to construct or acquire any new facilities or expand existing facilities, any such facilities shall be contracted, maintained, owned, and operated by Transporter, except as may otherwise be mutually agreed in writing. The design and installation of all facilities shall be in accordance with the specifications determined by Transporter.
SECTION 10 NOMINATIONS
A. If Shipper desires service under its transportation agreement on any day, Shipper shall give written notice of Shipper’s nomination to Transporter specifying the quantity of gas Shipper requests under each of Shipper’s transportation agreements for each day of the service month in accordance with the timeline provided herein. Such nomination should reflect the service for each Receipt Point and each Delivery Point, any imbalance correction quantities and any scheduled daily variations. Shipper shall furnish such nomination to Transporter by Transporter’s nomination system or other means acceptable to Transporter and such nomination shall also specify such information as Transporter determines is necessary in order to perform the service requested by Shipper. Receipts and deliveries of Gas herewith shall be at uniform hourly rates of flow unless otherwise mutually agreed by Shipper and Transporter. Transporter may assess a penalty of $0.50/MMBtu on a shipper whose actual volume is greater or less than 105% of scheduled volume. The penalty will be calculated by multiplying $0.50/MMBtu by the actual measured daily volume for the day when actual volumes are greater than or less than scheduled volumes.
B. For a Shipper’s initial wellhead nomination to be accepted for the first (1st) day of the service month, Shipper’s nomination must be received by Transporter by 1:00 p.m. Central Clock Time on the fourth (4th) business day prior to the last day of the month preceding the service month. For Shipper’s nominations at all other receipt or delivery points to be accepted for the first (1st) day of the service month, Shipper’s nominations must be received by Transporter by 1:00 p.m. Central Clock Time on the first (1st) business day prior to the last day of the month preceding the service month.
C. Shippers shall have the right, on or after the first (1st) day of the service month, to submit a new nomination or revise their existing nomination for any day during the service month provided such nomination is received by Transporter prior to 1:00 p.m. Central Clock Time on the business day prior to the day such new or revised service is requested to commence. Such new or revised nomination shall specify Shipper’s anticipated service requirements for the remainder of the service month. New or revised nominations shall be scheduled and implemented by Transporter on a prospective basis and only to the extent the Transporter is able to confirm the receipt and delivery of such gas with the operator of the Receipt Points and Delivery Points. If a conflict arises between Shipper’s new or revised nomination and the operator’s confirmation, Shipper understands and agrees such Receipt or Delivery Point operator’s confirmation shall control.
D. Transporter may, on a not unduly discriminatory basis, accept Shipper’s new or revised nomination if such nomination is received by Transporter after 1:00 p.m. Central Clock Time on the business day prior to the day such new or revised service is requested to commence. Such new or revised nomination shall specify Shipper’s anticipated service requirements for the remainder of the service month. New or revised nominations shall be scheduled and implemented by Transporter on a prospective basis and only to the extent the Transporter is able to confirm the receipt and delivery of such gas with the operator of the Receipt Points and Delivery Points. Such scheduling and implementation shall not “bump” any previously scheduled service. If a conflict arises between Shipper’s new or revised nomination and the operator’s confirmation, Shipper understands and agrees such Receipt or Delivery Point operator’s confirmation shall control.
E. All nominations will designate a person who will be responsible for coordinating notices between Transporter, well operator(s) and operators of the Shipper’s Receipt and Delivery Points in accordance with these procedures.
SECTION 11 SCHEDULING
Capacity in Transporter’s pipeline system shall be scheduled each day in the following order and manner:
A. Firm service shall receive first priority. Within this category, Transporter shall schedule nominated service as follows:
1. For transportation pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA, on a pro rata basis, and
2. For intrastate transportation, in accordance with the Curtailment Standards of the Railroad Commission of Texas set forth in 16 Texas Administrative Code, Section 7.455. Firm intrastate transportation service shall be scheduled in descending order as set forth below.
a. Firm deliveries to human needs customers and firm deliveries of natural gas to local distribution systems which serve human needs customers.
b. Firm deliveries to electric generation facilities.
c. Firm deliveries to industrial and commercial users of the minimum natural gas required to prevent physical harm and/or ensure critical safety to the plant facilities, to plant personnel, or the public when such protection cannot be achieved through the use of an alternate fuel.
d. Firm deliveries to small industrials and regular commercial loads that use less than 3,000 Mcf per day.
e. Firm deliveries to large industrial and commercial users for fuel or as a raw material where an alternate fuel or raw material cannot be used and operation and plant production would be curtailed or shut down completely when natural gas is curtailed.
f. Firm deliveries to large industrial and commercial users for fuel or as a raw material where an alternate fuel or raw material can be used and operation and plant production would be curtailed or shut down completely when natural gas is curtailed.
g. Firm deliveries to customers that are not covered by the priorities listed in subsections 1 through 6 above.
If Transporter is unable to schedule all nominations for firm intrastate transportation service in a subcategory above, gas will be scheduled within such subcategory on a pro rata basis based on the quantity that would otherwise be scheduled.
B. Interruptible service shall receive second priority. Within this category, Transporter shall schedule nominated service on an economic basis. As such, Transporter shall accord service paying a higher rate per MMBtu a higher priority than service paying a lower rate. If two or more Shippers are paying the same rate per MMBtu, Transporter shall schedule nominated service on a pro-rata basis.
C. Imbalance correction quantities nominated under any transportation agreement shall receive third priority. Within this category, Transporter shall schedule nominated service on a pro-rata basis.
SECTION 12 PRE-DETERMINED ALLOCATIONS
A. Operators of Central Receipt Points, Receipt Points and Delivery Points shall provide to Transporter a Pre-Determined Allocation (“PDA”); provided, however, such PDA must be acceptable to and capable of being implemented by Transporter. The PDA shall be used to allocate gas quantities at each Central Receipt Point, Receipt Point and Delivery Point.
B. For meters physically behind or attributable to a Central Receipt Point, the meter operators or their representative will provide the PDA at the Central Receipt Point meter.
C. All PDA’s shall be received in accordance with the nomination deadlines specified in Section 10.
D. In the event a PDA is not received from the operator, the PDA will default to a pro rata allocation. PDA’s received after the referenced deadlines may be accepted by Transporter on a not unduly discriminatory basis.
SECTION 13 BALANCING
A. Transporter will deliver to Shipper or its designee at the Delivery Point on daily basis quantities thermally equivalent to quantities received, less fuel, if applicable, unless otherwise mutually agreed to in writing. Transporter, upon notice to Shipper which shall be given at least twenty-four (24) hours in advance unless exigent circumstances dictate otherwise, may issue “Operational Flow Orders” to require adjustments to Shipper’s daily scheduling of receipts and/or deliveries over a reasonable period of time in order to maintain a concurrent balance when the operational integrity and/or safe operation of Transporter’s pipeline system would otherwise be threatened or result in inefficient or unreliable service. If Shipper does not comply with an Operational Flow Order then Transporter may assess a penalty for those volumes that flowed in violation of the OFO. The OFO penalty will equal the higher of $25/MMBtu or two (2) times the highest Gas Daily Houston Ship Channel midpoint during the month in which the OFO was declared.
B. If Shipper is advised by any upstream or downstream transporter or operator to reduce or suspend deliveries for transportation, Shipper shall immediately notify Transporter orally, and shall confirm such notification in writing, of such reduction or suspension, and adjust its nominations at Receipt Points and/or Delivery Points in order to maintain a balanced position.
C. Shipper shall be responsible for and shall bear any penalties imposed, claims made, or judgments (collectively called “Liability”) imposed by either (a) upstream and downstream transporters for imbalances between Central Receipt Points, Receipt Points and Delivery Points or (b) well operators or well interest owners for production imbalances among the interest owners in a well. Shipper shall indemnify and hold Transporter harmless from all such Liability, including court costs and reasonable attorney fees, unless such Liability is found to be the direct result of Transporter’s negligence.
D. Prior to initiating corrective action, absent conditions threatening Transporter’s system integrity or safe operations, Transporter will provide to Shipper information regarding any imbalance situation that has occurred or may occur unless corrective action is taken, and Shipper shall adjust nominations at Receipt Points and/or Delivery Points in order to maintain a balanced position. If Shipper believes such information is inaccurate, it shall immediately provide Transporter the information it believes to be contrary to Transporter’s conclusion for verification prior to corrective action.
SECTION 14 CURTAILMENT
A. Transporter shall have the right to curtail or discontinue transportation services in whole or in part on all or a portion of its system at any time for reasons of force majeure or when Transporter determines capacity or operating conditions so require or it is desirable or necessary to perform maintenance or to make modifications, repairs or operating changes to its system.
B. Transporter shall provide Shipper such notice of the curtailment as is reasonable under the circumstances. In the event curtailment of transportation service is required, service quantities shall be curtailed in the reverse order of the priority in effect at the time of curtailment established during scheduling as set forth in Section 11.
SECTION 15 FORCE MAJEURE
A. In the event Transporter or Shipper is rendered unable, wholly or in part, by reason of force majeure to carry out its obligations under the transportation agreement (other than the obligation to make payment of amounts due hereunder), it is agreed that such party shall give notice and reasonably full particulars of such force majeure, in writing, facsimile, or other electronic means to the other party within a reasonable time after the occurrence of the cause relied on, and the obligations of the party giving such notice, so far as they are affected by such force majeure, shall be suspended during the continuance of any inability so caused, but for no longer period, and such cause shall, so far as possible, be remedied with all reasonable dispatch. If sent by facsimile transmission, confirmation shall occur when receipt is confirmed by the equipment of the transmitting party.
B. The term, “force majeure,” as employed herein shall mean acts of God; strikes, lockouts, or other industrial disturbances; conditions arising from a change in governmental laws, orders, rules, or regulations; acts of public enemy; wars; blockades; insurrections; riots; epidemics; landslides; lightning; earthquakes; fires; storms; floods; washouts; arrests and restraints of governments and people; civil disturbances; explosions; breakage or accident to machinery or lines of pipe; the necessity for making repairs, tests, alterations, or performing maintenance to machinery or lines of pipe; scheduled maintenance; freezing of lines of pipe; or failure of processing facilities; and any other causes, whether of the kind herein enumerated or otherwise, not within the control of the party claiming relief hereunder, and which by the exercise of due diligence, such party is unable to prevent or overcome. Such term shall likewise include: (1) those instances where either Transporter or Shipper is required to obtain servitudes, rights-of-way, grants, permits or licenses to enable such party to fulfill its obligations under the transportation agreement; the inability of such party to acquire or the delays on the part of such party in acquiring, at reasonable costs, and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such servitudes, rights-of-way, grants, permits, or licenses, (2) those instances where either Transporter or Shipper is required to furnish materials and supplies for the purpose of constructing or maintaining facilities or is required to secure permits or permissions from any governmental agency to enable such party to fulfill its obligations under the transportation agreement, the inability of such party to acquire, or the delays on the part of such party in acquiring, at reasonable costs, and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such material and supplies, permits and permissions, and (3) in those instances in which Transporter utilizes facilities of another entity or entities to transport gas under the transportation agreement, the failure of such other entity or entities to transport such gas. Force majeure shall not include failure of gas supply due to pricing considerations.
C. It is understood and agreed that the settlement of strikes or lockouts shall be entirely within the discretion of the party having the difficulty, and that the above requirement that any force majeure shall be remedied with all reasonable dispatch shall not require the settlement of strikes or lockouts by acceding to the demands of the opposing party when such course is inadvisable in the discretion of the party having the difficulty.
D. Notwithstanding the foregoing, it is specifically understood and agreed by Transporter and Shipper that force majeure shall in no way terminate the parties’ obligations to resolve Imbalances in accordance with the terms provided for herein.
SECTION 16 CASH-OUT PROVISIONS
A. After the transportation month, Transporter will resolve all imbalances with Shipper through a cash payment or cash receipt, as applicable. To the extent that Shipper's delivered volumes are greater than Shipper's received volumes (“Due Pipeline”), Transporter will invoice Shipper for the imbalance based on the Net Monthly Imbalance multiplied by the Cash-out Price. To the extent that Shipper's delivered volumes are less than Shipper's received volumes (“Due Shipper”), Transporter will make a payment to Shipper for the imbalance based on the Net Monthly Imbalance multiplied by the Cash-out Price. The entire Net Monthly Imbalance will be valued at the Cash-out price as determined below.
B. The Net Monthly Imbalance is equal to the absolute value of the allocated Receipt volume less fuel less the allocated Delivery volume. The Shipper’s Imbalance Percentage is equal to the Net Monthly Imbalance divided by the Shipper’s allocated Delivered volumes. The Cash-out price shall be determined using the table below for either the excess (due Shipper - received is greater than delivered) or shortage (due Pipeline - received is less than delivered). If the Net Monthly Imbalance is less than one thousand (1,000) MMBtu, the Cash-out price shall be 100% of the Average Price.

C. 1. The “High Price” shall be equal to the greater of the highest Gas Daily Houston Ship Channel midpoint price or the highest of the applicable Delivery Point Prices, as identified in D below during the month in which the imbalance was generated. 2. The “Average Price” shall be equal to the greater of the arithmetic average of the Gas Daily Houston Ship Channel midpoint prices or the highest of the arithmetic averages of the applicable Delivery Point Prices, as identified in D below during the month in which the imbalance was generated. 3. The “Low Price” shall be equal to the lower of the lowest Gas Daily Houston Ship Channel midpoint price or the lowest of the applicable Delivery Point Prices, as identified in D below during the month in which the imbalance was generated. 4. Should the information necessary to calculate the High, Low or Average Price cease to be available, Transporter will determine a substitute publication providing equivalent data.
D. The Delivery Point Price is equal to the following midpoint price, during the month in which the imbalance was generated, based upon the Shipper’s delivery point: Florida Gas Transmission Company - Gas Daily Florida Gas, zone 1 Natural Gas Pipeline Company of America - Gas Daily NGPL, Texok zone Sabine Pipe Line LLC - Gas Daily Henry Hub Texas Eastern Transmission, LP (Vidor) - Gas Daily Texas Eastern, WLA Texas Eastern Transmission, LP (South Texas) - Gas Daily Texas Eastern, STX Trunkline Gas Company, LLC - Gas Daily Trunkline, WLA A Shipper may have more than one Delivery Point Price.
E. Pipeline Penalties. Any imbalance penalties, interest, and related costs imposed upon Transporter by pipelines attributable to Shipper’s over or under deliveries or other actions or omissions shall be paid by Shipper.
F. To the extent that Imbalances are caused or exacerbated by Shipper’s compliance with written or verbal flow directives (such compliance resulting in increases or decreases in Shipper’s nominations) or OFO issued by Transporter, the Cash-out price shall be equal to 100% of Average Price.
SECTION 17 MINIMUM QUANTITY
Transporter shall not be obligated to furnish service to any Shipper whose average annual gas quantity tendered for transportation is less than 300 MMBtu per day at any Receipt Point on Transporter’s transmission facilities. In the event the amount of gas subsequently tendered for delivery is less than the aforementioned minimum quantity, Transporter shall have the right to delete the Receipt Point that failed to meet the minimum quantity from the transportation agreement at any time upon fifteen (15) days written notice to Shipper. Transporter shall be deemed released from all obligations and liabilities, direct or indirect, related specifically to the continued acceptance of gas at the deleted Receipt Point under the transportation agreement upon the effective date of such deletion.
SECTION 18 QUALITY
A. All gas received or delivered hereunder shall conform to the following specifications:
1. Water: The gas shall not have a water content in excess of 7 pounds of water per million (1,000,000) cubic feet of gas measured at a pressure base of 14.73 pounds per square inch absolute and at a temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60° F).
2. Hydrogen Sulfide: The gas shall not contain more than ¼ grain of hydrogen sulfide per one hundred (100) cubic feet as determined by quantitative test.
3. Total Sulfur: The gas shall not contain more than four (4) grains of total sulfur per one hundred (100) cubic feet of gas as determined by quantitative test.
4. Temperature: The gas shall not have a temperature of less than forty degrees Fahrenheit (40° F), nor more than one hundred twenty degrees Fahrenheit (120° F).
5. Carbon Dioxide: The gas shall not contain carbon dioxide in excess of two percent (2%) by volume.
6. Oxygen: The gas shall not contain more than one tenth of one percent (0.1%) by volume of oxygen.
7. Nitrogen: The gas shall not contain nitrogen in excess of three percent (3%) by volume.
8. Non-hydrocarbons: The gas shall not contain more than four and one half percent (4½%) by volume of total non-hydrocarbons. Non-hydrocarbons shall include, but not be limited to, carbon dioxide, nitrogen, sulfur and hydrogen sulfide.
9. Objectionable Liquids and Solids, and Dilution: The gas shall be free of objectionable liquids and solids, and be commercially free from dust, gums, gumforming constituents, or other liquid or solid matter which might become separated from the gas in the course of transportation through pipelines.
10. Heating Value: The gas shall not have a heating value of less than 950 Btus per cubic foot.
11. Carbonyl Sulfide: The gas shall not contain carbonyl sulfide greater than 5 ppm of the propane as determined by quantitative test.
B. Notwithstanding A1 through A11 above, inclusive, all gas delivered or caused to be delivered by Shipper to Transporter at the Receipt Point(s) shall conform to the most strict quality specification of the downstream pipelines at the Delivery Points for each individual quality specification, any of which may be waived by Transporter in its discretion on a not unduly discriminatory basis.
C. Transporter shall not be obligated to accept gas hereunder, which does not conform to these specifications. In the event gas received hereunder does not conform to these quality specifications, Transporter shall notify Shipper of such nonconformance and Shipper shall immediately cease delivery of gas to Transporter or bring such gas within specification. Transporter may elect from time to time to receive such gas not conforming to the quality specifications herein. Transporter reserves the right to modify these quality specifications as the quality specifications of the downstream pipelines are modified. Acceptance by either party of gas that does not conform to the quality specifications stated above shall not constitute a waiver of such quality specifications by that party in regard to gas received or delivered under the transportation agreement in the future, nor shall acceptance without an express written waiver constitute a waiver of any claim for damages resulting from delivery of gas not meeting such specifications.
SECTION 19 BILLING AND PAYMENT
A. For the purpose of billing and accounting for the gas delivered hereunder, the day shall begin at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time and extend to 9:00 a.m. the following day, and the month (hereinafter called “billing month”) shall begin at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first day of the calendar month and extend to 9:00 a.m. on the first day of the following calendar month.
B. Transporter shall render or cause to be rendered, by mail, facsimile or other electronic means, to all Shippers an invoice of the amount due for the preceding month setting forth the total quantity of gas delivered by Transporter to Shipper at the Delivery Points and the rates for transportation hereunder during such billing month. Billings for quantities transported shall be determined on a dry basis. In computing the amounts due, Transporter may utilize estimates of the quantity of gas received from or delivered for the account of Shipper during a month, in place of actual quantities when actual quantities are not reasonably available; provided that adjustments shall be made in later statements for differences between such estimated and actual quantities. When information necessary for billing purposes is in the control of Shipper, Shipper’s gas seller, or Shipper’s downstream pipeline or purchaser, Shipper shall furnish such information to Transporter on or before the fifth (5th) day of the calendar month following the month of transportation.
C. Within ten (10) days from date of the invoice, Shipper shall pay Transporter the amount due for all gas delivered by Transporter for the account of Shipper during the preceding month. Payments to Transporter shall be made by wire transfer crediting Transporter, such that funds are available to Transporter on or before the tenth (10th) day after the date of the invoice. If rendering of an invoice by Transporter is delayed after the fifteenth (15th) day of the month, then the time of payment shall be extended accordingly unless Shipper is responsible for such delay.
D. Good Faith Dispute. If a portion of an invoice is disputed, Shipper shall pay when due the portion of the invoice not in dispute and shall at the same time provide Transporter with documentation supporting its dispute.
E. Late Payment. In the event Shipper fails to forward the entire undisputed amount due to Transporter when same is due, interest on the unpaid portion shall accrue at a rate equal to two percent (2%) above the prime rate published in the Wall Street Journal, from time to time, or the maximum legal rate, whichever is the lesser, compounded daily from the date such payment is due until the same is paid Shipper shall not be required to pay interest on any amount billed which is in good faith disputed in writing by Shipper and is ultimately determined to be in error; provided, however, interest shall be due if such amount billed is found not to be in error.
F. Examination of Books, Records and Charts. Transporter and Shipper shall have the right during reasonable working hours and after execution of a confidentiality agreement to examine the books, records and charts of the other to the extent necessary to verify the accuracy of any statement, payment calculations or determinations made pursuant to the provision contained herein. The accuracy of any statement, payment calculations or determinations made pursuant to the provisions contained herein shall be conclusively presumed to be correct after two (2) years from the end of the calendar year in which the charts and records were generated or prepared if not challenged in writing prior thereto. If any such examination shall reveal, or if Transporter or Shipper shall discover, any error in its own or the other party’s statements, payment calculations or determinations, then proper adjustment and correction thereof shall be made as promptly as practicable thereafter.
SECTION 20 MEASUREMENT
A. The gas delivered to the Receipt and Delivery Points shall be measured with meters constructed and installed, and whose computations of quantity are made, in accordance with the provisions of API 14.3 –AGA Report #3, AGA Report #9 or the latest revision thereof as adopted by Transporter.
B. The temperature of the gas shall be determined by a recording thermometer so installed that it will record the temperature of the gas flowing through the meters. The average of the record to the nearest one degree (1°) Fahrenheit, obtained while gas is being delivered, shall be the applicable flowing gas temperature for the period under consideration. For all measurement of gas required in this Section, the Btu content per cubic foot shall be determined for a cubic foot of gas at a temperature of sixty degrees (60°) Fahrenheit, at an absolute pressure of 14.73 pounds per square inch on a dry basis.
C. The Btu, specific gravity, carbon dioxide, nitrogen and hydrocarbon content of the gas delivered to the Receipt or Delivery Points shall be determined by the use of an on-line chromatograph or by a chromatographic analysis of the gas obtained by a continuous sample or spot sampling method. The results of any sample taken with an on-line chromatograph or continuous sampler shall be applied to the month in which the sample was taken. The results of any spot sample taken shall be applied to the month succeeding the month in which the sample was taken.
1. Delivery Points with consistent quantities of 25,000 Mcf per day or greater will have an on-line gas chromatograph, subject to adequate site facilities being available, including the availability of electricity and land to accommodate the necessary equipment, otherwise a continuous Btu sampler will be used to determine gas quality. Upon mutual agreement by the parties, an alternate method of measurement may be used.
2. Receipt Points with quantities equal to or less than 25,000 Mcf per day will use, at Transporter’s option, either a spot sampling technique or a continuous sampling technique.
D. Adjustment for the effect of supercompressibility shall be made according to the provisions of the latest version of AGA Committee Report No. 8, as required by Paragraph A of this section and as adopted by Transporter, for the average conditions of pressure, flowing temperature, and specific gravity at which the gas was measured during the period under consideration and with the proportionate values each of carbon dioxide, nitrogen and other applicable constituent in the gas delivered included in the computation of the applicable supercompressibility factors.
E. If at any time during the term hereof a new method or technique is developed with respect to gas measurement or the determination of the factors used in such gas measurement, such new method or technique may be substituted for the gas measurement set forth in this Section on the date such method or technique is adopted by Transporter.
SECTION 21 MEASURING EQUIPMENT AND TESTING
A. Installation and Operation. The construction, ownership, operation and maintenance of any measuring facilities necessary to accomplish the receipt of gas by Transporter for the account of Shipper at the Receipt Points and the delivery of gas for the account of Shipper at the Delivery Points shall be the responsibility of Transporter or designee. Each party shall at all reasonable times have access to the premises of the other for inspections, insofar as such premises are connected with any matter covered hereby. The operation of measuring equipment, changing of charts and/or collection of information shall be done only by the employees or agents of Transporter at the Receipt Points and the Delivery Points.
B. Testing and Repair of Equipment.
1. Transporter and Shipper shall keep their own measuring equipment accurate and in repair, making such periodic tests to verify the condition of meter tubes, orifice plate, and flow computer. Such periodic tests shall be performed, at a minimum, on a quarterly basis for Receipt Points and a monthly basis for Delivery Points, unless mutually agreed otherwise. Both parties agree to give each other or their designee seven (7) calendar days notice prior to such tests of the measuring equipment so that, if desired, either party may have its representative present. Either party shall have the right to challenge the accuracy of the other party’s equipment, and when challenged, the equipment shall be tested, calibrated and, if required, repaired by the challenged party, the cost of such special test to be borne by the challenged party if the inaccuracy is found to cause the total measured Btu during a month to be more than one percent (1%) of such total measured Btu, but if the inaccuracy is found to cause the total measured Btu during a month to be one percent (1%) or less of such total measured Btu, the cost of such special test shall be borne by the challenging party. If upon any equipment test the inaccuracy and all prior inaccuracies resulting from other equipment tests during the same period are found to cause the total measured Btu during a month to be in excess of one percent (1%) of such total measured Btu and the total measurement adjustment during a month is greater than 100 MMBtu, then the registrations thereof shall be corrected for a period extending back to the time such inaccuracy occurred, if such time is ascertainable, and if such time is not ascertainable, then back one-half (1/2) of the time elapsed since the last date of equipment calibration. If upon any equipment test the inaccuracy and all prior inaccuracies resulting from other equipment tests covering the same period are found to cause the total measured Btu during a month to be less than one percent (1%) of such total measured Btu or the total measurement adjustment during a month is less than 100 MMBtu, then, the operator of the measuring equipment may cause the registrations thereof to be corrected for a period extending back to the time such inaccuracy occurred, if such time is ascertainable, and if such time not ascertainable, then back one-half (1/2) of the time elapsed since the last date of calibration. Any measuring equipment found to be measuring inaccurately in any percentage shall be adjusted at once to read accurately.
2. If, for any reason, the meter(s) are out of service or out of repair so that the amount of gas received and/or delivered cannot be ascertained or computed from the readings thereof, the gas received and/or delivered during the period such meter(s) are out of service or out of repair shall be estimated and agreed upon by the parties hereto by the use of the first applicable of the following methods:
a. By comparative utilization of any like check measuring equipment installed by Shipper or Shipper’s designee if such check measuring equipment can be proven and verified to be measuring accurately subject to the check meter provisions in Paragraph E of this section; or
b. By computing the error if the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, test or mathematical calculation; or
c. By estimating the quantity received and/or delivered by reference to actual receipts and/or deliveries during preceding periods under similar conditions when Transporter’s measuring equipment was registering accurately.
C. Pulsation Induced Measurement Errors and Reduction
1. To ensure orifice metering accuracy, pulsation induced orifice measurement errors shall not exceed .25% Square Root Error (SRE) during any diagnostic testing. Orifice measurement facilities and related piping elements included in this contract found to exhibit excessive SRE levels shall be modified to suppress pulsation effects below .25% SRE. The installation of impulse line snubbers or excessive dampening of bellows type meters are unacceptable practices in the effort to reduce pulsation effects. Acceptable practices include the installation of in-line acoustic filter bottles/chokes or in-line restrictive orifices. The use of in-line restrictive orifices should be used for short-term pulsation reduction until acoustic filter bottles can be installed, particularly in high SRE pulsation environments.
2. The party responsible for inducing pulsation related measurement errors shall bear the cost for the design, fabrication, installation and operation of the necessary remedial equipment or devices, including consulting fees for diagnostic work.
3. If operating conditions (i.e., flow rates, compressor operating speeds, pressures) change significantly after the installation of the pulsation suppression equipment/devices, the responsible party shall initiate follow-up pulsation testing to ensure that the remedial equipment or devices are maintaining SRE levels below .25% SRE. If SRE levels are excessive after the re-testing, the responsible party shall modify or redesign the remedial equipment or devices to maintain SRE below .25%.
4. Remedial actions necessary to bring SRE levels to acceptable levels must be completed within 30 days from the date of diagnostic testing. Failure to comply with this requirement will result in potential well or station shut-in. At the gatherer’s discretion, retroactive volume adjustments can be made based on the results of diagnostic testing.
D. Inspection of Data and Records. The data and records from the measuring equipment shall remain the property of Transporter and shall be kept on file for a period of time not less than two (2) years from the end of the calendar year in which the charts and records were generated or prepared. At any time within such period, upon written request by Shipper, records and/or data from the measuring equipment, together with calculations therefrom, will be submitted for Shipper’s inspection and verification subject to return to Transporter within thirty (30) days from receipt thereof. Shipper or Shipper’s designee shall retain its charts and records for the same period of time as Transporter’s obligation under this paragraph. Any inquiries regarding measurement equipment and testing, including but not limited to, measurement charts, records, or audits of charts and records shall be directed to Manager, Measurement.
E. Telemetering. Transporter and Shipper shall each have the right, but not the obligation, to install and operate telemetering equipment it deems necessary to carry out Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition (SCADA) or other operational needs at any Receipt and/or Delivery Points contemplated hereunder, provided Transporter’s normal operations are not impeded. Custody measurement taps will not be shared under any circumstance.
F. Check Meter. Shipper or Shipper’s designee shall have the right to install, maintain as described in Paragraph A of this Section, and operate such check measurement equipment as it may desire, but same shall not interfere with or impede in any way the operation of Transporter’s measurement or other equipment hereunder, and all calibrating and adjusting of check meters and changing of charts shall be done by Shipper or its designees. Such check meters may be installed at the Receipt Points only, unless the Delivery Points are at Shipper’s or its designee’s pipeline. Further, Transporter must be notified seven (7) calendar days prior to all testing and calibration in order to have a representative present. In the event Transporter proves the inaccuracy of Shipper’s check meter or all applicable check meter maintenance records are not available, both parties agree to incorporate the next applicable alternate method detailed in Paragraph B.2 of this Section to resolve the discrepancy.
SECTION 22 RECEIPT AND DELIVERY PRESSURES
A. All gas delivered hereunder by Shipper shall be delivered at pressures sufficient to enter Transporter’s pipeline system at the working pressures maintained at the Receipt Points from time to time. Transporter shall not be obligated to receive gas hereunder at pressures exceeding the maximum allowable operating pressures of the facilities or pressures prescribed under any applicable governmental regulations. Transporter shall at no time be required, unless otherwise agreed in writing, to construct or modify facilities currently existing, including compression, to effect such receipt, including but not limited to, instances when the upstream facility changes its operating conditions from those in effect at the time the interconnection was completed.
B. All gas delivered hereunder by Transporter shall be delivered at pressures sufficient to enter the downstream facilities at the working pressures maintained at the Delivery Points from time to time. Transporter shall not be obligated to deliver gas hereunder at pressures exceeding the maximum allowable operating pressures of the facilities or pressures prescribed under any applicable governmental regulations. Notwithstanding the foregoing, Transporter shall at no time be required, unless otherwise agreed in writing, to construct or modify facilities currently existing, including compression, to effect such delivery including, but not limited to, instances when the downstream facility changes its operating conditions from those in effect at the time the interconnection was completed. If Transporter chooses to modify compression, a compression fee may be assessed to Shipper.
SECTION 23 MISCELLANEOUS
A. BASIC FUNCTION. Transporter is first and foremost an intrastate pipeline. Therefore, any Section 311(a)(2) service that Transporter provides will be consistent with and shall not infringe upon its status as a non-jurisdictional intrastate pipeline and shall not subject Transporter to the FERC’s Natural Gas Act jurisdiction.
B. REGULATORY STATUS OF GAS
1. Whenever Shipper’s Gas is delivered to a Receipt Point or received from a Delivery Point that is not an interconnect with the facilities of an interstate pipeline company, Shipper shall (unless Shipper shall expressly advise Transporter otherwise in writing at the time of submitting its nomination to Transporter) be deemed to have represented and warranted to Transporter that all of the Gas so delivered to Transporter or received from Transporter shall (i) have been produced in the State of Texas from reserves not dedicated or committed to interstate commerce, (ii) not be or have not been received from or transported through any interstate pipeline company or any intrastate pipeline company which claims exemption from the provisions of the Natural Gas Act of 1938 pursuant to Section 1(c) thereof, and (iii) not have been or be commingled at any point with Gas which is received from or transported through any interstate pipeline company or any intrastate pipeline company which claims exemption from the provisions of the Natural Gas Act of 1938 pursuant to Section 1(c) thereof, or with Gas which is or may be sold, consumed, transported, or otherwise utilized in interstate commerce, in such a manner which will subject the Gas delivered by or to Shipper hereunder or any of Transporter’s or its affiliate’s pipeline, transmission, storage or related facilities, or any portions thereof, to the jurisdiction of the FERC or any successor authority incident to the provisions of Section 1(b) or Section 1(c) of the Natural Gas Act of 1938 (the “NGA”).
2. Whenever (i) Shipper’s Gas is delivered to a Receipt Point or received from a Delivery Point that is an interconnection between the Pipeline and the facilities of an interstate pipeline company or (ii) Shipper expressly advises Transporter in the manner contemplated in the first sentence of Section 23.B.1 above), Shipper shall be deemed to have represented and warranted to Transporter that transportation of Gas hereunder is “on behalf of” an interstate pipeline company or a local distribution company served by an interstate pipeline company and otherwise qualifies as transportation pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA and FERC’s rules, regulations and orders thereunder. If requested by Transporter, Shipper shall provide evidence satisfactory to Transporter that the service provided hereunder is “on behalf of” an interstate pipeline company or a local distribution company served by an interstate pipeline company, and that such service otherwise qualifies as transportation pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA and the Commission’s rules, regulations and orders thereunder.
3. Transporter shall have no obligation under this Agreement if Transporter determines at any time that Shipper has breached any applicable representation or warranty referenced above or that the transportation to be provided hereunder does not so qualify. Shipper agrees to indemnify and hold Transporter harmless from and against and shall compensate Shipper for any and all actions, damages, costs, losses and expenses sustained by Transporter relative to any breach by Shipper of any representation or warranty herein expressed.
C. CHANGES TO THIS STATEMENT. Transporter reserves the right to add, delete or modify conditions in this Statement of Operating Conditions at any time in accordance with the FERC’s Regulations under 18 CFR Section 284.123(e). A copy of the revised Statement of Operating Conditions will be furnished to Shippers who request it.
D. CONFLICTS AND AUTHORITY OF STATEMENT. The rules and regulations of the jurisdictional agency govern all services provided under Section 311(a)(2), and in the event any service agreement term or provision is inconsistent with these rules and regulations or this Statement of Operating Conditions, the rules and regulations or this Statement of Operating Conditions will control and the contract will be deemed modified accordingly.
E. POSSESSION AND NON-ODORIZATION OF GAS. As between Shipper and Transporter, Shipper shall be in exclusive control and possession of the gas deliverable and responsible for any damage or injury caused thereby until the same shall have been received by Transporter for the account of Shipper at the Receipt Points and after delivery of the gas by Transporter for the account of Shipper at the Delivery Points. After delivery of gas by Shipper to Transporter, and until delivery by Transporter to Shipper or Shipper’s designee, Transporter shall be in exclusive control and possession thereof and responsible for any injury or damage caused thereby. The Receipt and Delivery Points hereunder shall be deemed to be located at the flanges connecting the facilities owned by Transporter with those facilities owned, leased or used by Shipper or Shipper’s designee or its gas supplier for the receipt and delivery of gas hereunder. Each party expressly notifies the other that the gas delivered to the Receipt and Delivery Points hereunder is not odorized. In the event that either party, at its own election or pursuant to laws, orders, rules or regulations of any governmental body having jurisdiction, elects or is required to odorize the gas deliverable hereunder, then such party shall give prior written notice to the other of its intention to odorize such gas.
F. TITLE AND RISK OF LOSS. Shipper warrants for itself, its successors and assigns, that it will have at the time of delivery of Gas at the Receipt Point hereunder either good title or all rights necessary and appropriate to have the Gas transported. Shipper warrants for itself, its successors and assigns, that the Gas it delivers hereunder shall be free and clear of all liens, encumbrances and claims on the title to the Gas; and that it will indemnify and hold harmless Transporter, its officers, agents, employees and contractors from and against any and all suits, claims, liability, loss, damages, costs (including attorney’s fees and court costs) or encumbrances whatsoever arising directly or indirectly from and with respect to the title and/or right to Gas tendered to Transporter hereunder. Transporter warrants that at the time of delivery to Shipper at the Delivery Point the gas delivered hereunder shall be free and clear of all liens, encumbrances and claims on the title to the Gas; and that it will indemnify and hold harmless Shipper, its officers, agents, employees and contractors against any and all suits, claims, liability, loss, damages, costs (including attorney’s fees and court costs) or encumbrances whatsoever arising directly or indirectly from or with respect to the title and/or right to Gas tendered delivered to Shipper as a result of Transporter’s possession or transportation hereunder. Title and/or rights to all Gas delivered by Shipper to Transporter for transportation, hereunder will remain with Shipper during transport by Transporter; provided, however, it is understood and agreed that the Gas delivered at the Point(s) of Delivery will not be the identical Gas that was delivered to Transporter for transportation, hereunder, but such Gas will be a part of the commingled delivery of Gas and, for the purpose of Shipper’s service agreement, the commingled Gas may be substituted for Shipper’s Gas on a heat-equivalent basis.
G. GOVERNING LAWS AND REGULATIONS. The interpretation and performance of any transportation agreement that is subject to this Statement of Operating Conditions shall be governed by, construed, interpreted and enforced in accordance with the substantive laws of the State of Texas, without reference to its choice of law doctrine. Transporter’s transportation services are subject to all present and future valid lawful orders of all regulatory authorities now or hereafter having jurisdiction of the services or facilities used to provide such services, including, without limitation, the provisions of Subpart C of Part 284 of the Commission’s Regulations. In the event any regulatory body having jurisdiction over the transportation service prohibits Transporter from collecting specific rates for the services provided under the Transportation Agreement or subjects its transportation facilities to any greater or different regulation or jurisdiction than that existing on the date of initial transportation service hereunder (or thereafter as such regulation or jurisdiction may have changed and been accepted), then Transporter shall have the right to terminate the Transportation Agreement on the effective date of such regulation, anything herein to the contrary notwithstanding and shall have no liability to Shipper or any other entity in connection with any such termination.
H. ARBITRATION.
1. In the event the Transporter and Shipper are unable to resolve any dispute regarding the application or interpretation of any provision of a transportation agreement or related transaction such dispute shall be resolved through mandatory arbitration under the Rules of the Center For Public Resources Institute For Dispute Resolution, to the extent not inconsistent with the rules specified herein.
2. Within twenty (20) business days of either Transporter’s or Shipper’s written election to the other to arbitrate any disputes which arise under this Agreement, each party shall choose one arbitrator, and within ten (10) Business Days after both such arbitrators are chosen, such arbitrators shall choose a third arbitrator thus completing the whole arbitration panel. Any arbitrator chosen shall be a disinterested party with knowledge of the industry. Any arbitration hereunder shall be conducted in Houston, Texas. Any transaction entered into and governed by this Statement shall be construed in accordance with and governed by the laws of the State of Texas.
3. The arbitrator(s), once chosen, shall consider any evidence which the arbitrators deem necessary and shall then accept sealed written resolutions of the subject dispute from each party on a confidential basis to be submitted within twenty (20) Business Days of establishment of the arbitration panel. The written submissions shall be in a form and subject to any limitations as may be prescribed by the arbitrators. The arbitrators shall then choose only one of the proposed solutions, (without modification) as the fairest solution to the dispute within ten (10) Business Days of receipt of the written submissions of both parties. In the event of a three-member arbitration panel, a majority vote shall govern. The decision of the arbitrators shall be final and non-appealable.
4. Any expenses incurred in connection with hiring the arbitrators and performing the arbitration shall be shared and paid equally between the parties. Each party shall bear and pay its own expenses incurred in connection with the arbitration, unless otherwise included in a solution chosen by the arbitration panel. In the event either party must file a court action to enforce an arbitration award under this Section, the prevailing party shall be entitled to recover its court costs and reasonable attorney fees. In respect of any suit, action, claim or proceeding relating to this Agreement, each party hereby waives, to the fullest extent permitted by law, any right to jury trial. The existence, contents or results of any arbitration hereunder may not be disclosed without the prior written consent of both parties. The parties submit to the exclusive jurisdiction of the state and federal courts of the State of Texas.
I. LIMITATIONS OF REMEDIES, LIABILITY AND DAMAGES. NO PARTY SHALL BE LIABLE FOR CONSEQUENTIAL, INCIDENTAL, PUNITIVE, EXEMPLARY OR INDIRECT DAMAGES, LOST PROFITS OR OTHER BUSINESS INTERRUPTION DAMAGES, BY STATUTE, IN TORT OR CONTRACT, UNDER ANY INDEMNITY PROVISION OR OTHERWISE. THE LIMITATIONS IMPOSED ON REMEDIES AND THE MEASURE OF DAMAGES BE WITHOUT REGARD TO THE CAUSE OR CAUSES RELATED THERETO, INCLUDING THE NEGLIGENCE OF ANY PARTY, WHETHER SUCH NEGLIGENCE BE SOLE, JOINT OR CONCURRENT, OR ACTIVE OR PASSIVE.
J. ASSIGNMENT. Any transportation agreement that is governed by this Statement of Operating Conditions shall be binding upon and inure to the benefit of the successors, assigns, personal representatives, and heirs of the respective Shipper and Transporter. No assignment of such transportation agreement, in whole or in part, shall be made by Shipper without the prior written consent of Transporter, which consent will not be unreasonably withheld, provided, however, Shipper may transfer its interest to any affiliate by assignment, merger or otherwise or to the purchaser or acquirer of substantially all the assets of Shipper (whether by sale, merger or otherwise) without prior written consent of Transporter as long as Shipper’s successor entity has a credit status which, the Transporter determines is at least equal to or higher than that of Shipper.
